{
  "How do you solve equations with variables on both sides?": "",
  "Move all variable terms to one side and constants to the other": "",
  "What is a contradiction?": "",
  "An equation that simplifies to a false statement (e.g., 0 = 5) — no solution": "",
  "What is an identity?": "",
  "An equation true for all values of the variable (e.g., 0 = 0) — infinitely many solutions": "",
  "Solve: 4x + 2 = 2x + 10": "",
  "2x = 8 → x = 4": "",
  "Solve: 3x − 7 = 3x + 5": "",
  "−7 = 5 — no solution (contradiction)": "",
  "Solve: 2(x + 1) = 2x + 2": "",
  "2x + 2 = 2x + 2 → 0 = 0 — infinitely many solutions": "",
  "If you get 0 = 0(x), the equation has how many solutions?": "",
  "Infinitely many solutions (identity)": "",
  "If you get a false statement like 5 = 0, the equation has?": "",
  "No solution (contradiction)": "",
  "Solve: 5x − 3 = 2x + 9": "",
  "3x = 12 → x = 4": "",
  "When should you check your solution?": "",
  "Always — especially when the equation may be a contradiction or identity": ""
